SIMPLE: tire
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tire
<hw>Tire</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A tier, row, or rank. See
<er>Tier</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In posture to displode their second <qex>tire</qex>⟦br⟧
Of thunder.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tire
<hw>Tire</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Aphetic form of <ets>attire</ets>;
OE. <ets>tir</ets>, <ets>a tir</ets>. See <er>Attire</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Attire; apparel.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Having rich <xex>tire</xex> about you.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A covering for the head; a headdress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On her head she wore a <qex>tire</qex> of gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A child's apron, covering the breast and having no
sleeves; a pinafore; a tier.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Furniture; apparatus; equipment.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>tire</xex> of war.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Philips.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[Probably the same word, and so called as being an
attire or covering for the wheel.]</ety> <def>A ring, hoop or band, as
of rubber or metal, on the circumference of the wheel of a vehicle, to
impart strength and receive the wear. In Britain, spelled
<asp>tyre</asp>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The iron <xex>tire</xex> of a wagon wheel or cart wheel
binds the fellies together. The <xex>tire</xex> of a locomotive or
railroad-car wheel is a heavy hoop of iron or steel shrunk tightly upon
an iron central part. The wheel of a bicycle or road vehicle
(automobile, motorcyle, truck) has a <xex>tire</xex> of rubber, which is
typically hollow inside and inflated with air to lessen the shocks from
bumps on uneven roads.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tire
<hw>Tire</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To adorn; to attire; to
dress.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Jezebel] painted her face, and <qex>tired</qex> her head.</q>
<rj><qau>2 Kings ix. 30.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Tire
<hw>Tire</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>tirer</ets> to draw or
pull; of Teutonic origin, and akin to E. <ets>tear</ets> to rend. See
<er>Tirade</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To seize, pull, and tear prey,
as a hawk does.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Even as an empty eagle, sharp by fast,⟦br⟧
<qex>Tires</qex> with her beak on feathers, flesh, and bone.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye dregs of baseness, vultures among men,⟦br⟧
That <qex>tire</qex> upon the hearts of generous spirits.</q>
<rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To seize, rend, or tear something as prey; to be
fixed upon, or engaged with, anything.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus made she her remove,⟦br⟧
And left wrath <qex>tiring</qex> on her son.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon that were my thoughts <qex>tiring</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Tire
<hw>Tire</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tired</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tiring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>teorien</ets> to become
weary, to fail, AS. <ets>teorian</ets> to be tired, be weary, to tire,
exhaust; perhaps akin to E. <ets>tear</ets> to rend, the intermediate
sense being, perhaps, to wear out; or cf. E. <ets>tarry</ets>.]</ety>
<def>To become weary; to be fatigued; to have the strength fail; to have
the patience exhausted; <as>as, a feeble person soon
<ex>tires</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Tire
<hw>Tire</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To exhaust the strength of, as by
toil or labor; to exhaust the patience of; to wear out (one's interest,
attention, or the like); to weary; to fatigue; to jade.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Tired</qex> with toil, all hopes of safety past.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To tire out</b></col>, <cd>to weary or fatigue to
exhaustion; to harass.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To jade; weary; exhaust; harass. See
<er>Jade</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tired</ent>⟦br⟧
